ge of the chumpagne hill will do much\nto obviate further trouble in tho disaf\nfected district, it is believed.\nPipo tho Best Smoko.\nM, Schloosing of tho Institute of Sci\nence, in a recent address condemns cigar\nettes, tolerates cigars and is enthusiastic\nas regards pipe smoking. M. Schlocsing\ndemonstrated that the combustion of to\nbacco In a pipe produces a greater quan\ntily of formic aldehyde than combustion\nIn \"a cigarette. Inasmuch as formic aldc\nlivde acts in diminishing the injurious\nelement of nicotine, this is to the advan\ntage of the pipe.\nA vast crowd assembled at a fashion\nable skating rink orf the Champs Elyees\nthe other night, where three handsome\nwomen whirled round the building attired\nIn harem skirts, .on the arms of skating\nteachers.\nThere was a general tendency among\nthe onlookers to deride tho new fashion\nand ridicule the women.\nBig Guns Pail at Tost.\nIn the course of recent firing practice\nVt by the battleship licet the turrets of the\nM twelve-inch guns and the guns them-\nselves became jammed and out of use on\nboard five ships out of six.\nAdmiral Bclluc ordered simultaneous\nfiring by the twelve-inch guns of tho main\nturrets. Tho shock damaged the guns\nand turrets and rendered further firing\nimpossible on the live ships. The Demo\ncrate and the Justice suffered chiefly.\nThey have been handed over to the dock\nyard authorities for repairs.\nA councilor of the prefecture, a slate\nofficial, has applied for his pension on\nthe ground that he is suffering chronic\ndyspepsia as a result of fulfilling his du-\n$1000\n\"I wouldn't take a thousand\ndollars for the good VINOL has\ndone me. I was told that Cod Liver\nOil was the medicine I needed for\nmy weakened condition and poor\nblood. I could not take the greasy\nmixture, and when our druggist told\nme that VINOL contained not only\ntonic iron but all the medicinal prop\nerties of Cod Liver Oil without the\ngrease or oil or bad taste, I made\nup my mind that was the medicine\nfor me. I tried it and to-day am\nstrong and well.\"\nMrs. J. T. Snyder,\nGreensboro, N. C.\n\"Wo trnnrnnteo the genuineness of tho\nnboTo testimonial.\nWe sell VINOL with die\nunderstanding that if it does\nnot give the purchaser per\nfect satisfaction, we return\nhis money without question.\nWill you try a bottle un\nder these conditions?\nDruohl Frankon, 271 Main; Smith\nDrug Co., \"Tho Busy Comer;\" Smith\nI Drug Co. No. 2, Kcnyon liotol block,\n215 Main street.\ntics in attending stato banquets. Tho\ncabinet, unwilling to associate itself with\nwhat would be a grave :ilur on chefs, has\nrejected tho dyspeptic official's demand.\nThe latest society fad is tho dog visit\ning card. \"Poms'1 and pugs which go\nvisiting with their mistressoB in fash\nI ionablo circles have their own tiny pasto\nhoards tucked away in lilUo pockets.\nSuch dogs havo two sets of cards, which\nare left on other dogs at 'tho houses\nwhere they call with their mistresses.\nOne card given tho dog's name, whilo\nthe other records its pet namo joined to\nthe familv name of Its owner.\nJean Lavellc, a tourist who has just\nreturned, relates that somo time ago ho\nsot out across tho St. Bernard pass by\nhimself and got caught in tho fog. Ho\nsat. on a rock and waited for ono of tho\ndogs to come, but in vain, and when tho\nfog cleared away ho managed to reach\nthe hospice.\n\"There I was,\" he said, \"for six hours;\nand not one came near mo.\"\n\"But why,\" exclaimed ono of tho monks,\n\"why did you not ring us up on tho telo\nphorie?\" Tho astonished tourist learned then\nthat the wholo pass Is provided with\nshelters at short distances from each\nother, all in direct telephonic communica\ntion with the hospice. When the bcl!\nrings tho monk sends off a dog, loaded\nwith bread and other comforts. The\ndog on duty Is told what number has\nrung and he goes straight to that shelter.\nThis system saves the dogs their old\nduty of patrolling the pass on tho chanco\nof finding a stray traveler, which, as the\npass Is under snow for about ciglit\nmonths of the year, entailed hard and\noften fruitless labor.\nBishop Answers Last Call.\nBy Associated Press.\nSAN' ANTONIO. Tex.. March 11. Right\nRev. John Anthony Forest, bishop of the\nRoman Catholic dioceso of San Antonio,\nTexas, died in tho Santa Rosa infirmary\nhero today, aged 73 years.\nWater, -water everywhere, but none\nfit to drink. American Beauty Beer\nby. the case .costs less, than 10 cents\na bottle. Run no chances \"with filthy\nwater, but order a case today. Phones\n17. Salt Lako City Brewing Co.\nThe bright spot in town. High class\nentertainment.\" Cuisino unexcelled.\nTho Rathskeller Cafe, 2nd South and\nMain.\nII 6 T T Z fr'A'TC'S rising at six o 'clock'\nI I I I I u e monuS living on a\nI dollar a day if you earn two.\nI Minding your own business and not\nI meddling with other people's. Luck\nmeans appointments you have never failed to I\n\"keep. The trains you have never I\nfaiLecL, to catch. Luck means trusting in I\nGod and your own resources.\" 1\nThe man with a bank account and z, check\nI book in his pocket is considered lucky. This\n1 S kind of luck is within your easy reach. Many\n1 L of our best customers started with a small\n1 r' deposit. So can you.\nYOURSELF and Friends are cordially \"invited\nto do your banking with\n1 Utah Savings Trust I\nH Trie Home of Four Per Cent and Safety I\nJ 235 South Main St I\n9\nsum mm\nI I MONEY-SAVING SALE I\nI on a few of our high grade 1\nI i Gas Ranges\n9 k v I Preparatory to receiving several additional carloads of gas ranges fl\n1 1 we l nccessary to movo and re-arrango our present stock. R\nl! M In order to reduce It quickly -we are offering a limited number of 1\n1 new and slightly used ranges at\nH I RE AT BARGAINS 1\n9 1 They must move 1nIckIy and yu will And it much to your ad- I\n1 vantage to make your selections at once. Our representative will caU 1\nI j I on request to furnish further information.\ni I UTAH GAS COKE CO.\nI 61-65 MAIN STREET. t PHONES 4321. 1\nIn Fact, Many Now Find Com\nmerce Commission Ruling\nHas Many Benefits.\nMAY HELP TO KEEP\nLIVING COST DOWN\nNew Rules in Wall Street Give\nMan Who Buys Some Rights\nas Investor.\nBY PRESTON 0. ADAMS.\nBy Leased \"VVlro to Th Tribune.\nNEW YORK, March 11. Now that tho\nfreight rato decision of tho Interstate\ncommerce commission him been digested,\ntho railroads have decided not to go to\nsmash after all, but will do buslnoas In\nabout tho saino old way. In faot, somo\nof tho railroad magnates havo about\ncomo to tho concluolon that tho decision\nmay not be an unmixed ovll after all.\nIt la pointed out that tho greatest\nenemy of American capital during recont\nyears has been hostllo public sentiment.\nThe uncompromising stand taken by the\nlntcrstato commerco commission should,\nand probably will, disarm criticism that\ntho railroad can levy unreasonable\ncharges upon tho people. Such a con\nquest Is worth moro to the corporations\nthan any sum that could havo been de\nrived from tho proposed Increase In\nfreight rates.\nIf tho ruling also has tho offect of\nchecking tho aggressiveness of stato com\nmissions, now that the fedoral body has\ntaken offectlvo action, anothor great good\nwill have boon accomplished. Tho eco\nnomic readjustment which has been in\nprogress for twclvo months will bo ac\ncelerated, whereas the granting of higher\ncharges would havo tended to perpetuato\nthe vicious circle of rising prices. Did\nnot labor leaders plead, for tho proposed\nadvances on tho gTourid that thereafter\nwages might bo again raised? This has\nbeen checked.\nHero Are Somo Benefits.\nOpulence begets extravagance: neces\nsity stimulates economy. American rail\nroad companies havo been lavish In their\nexpenditures upon what might bo called\ntho ornamental, as witness tho erection\nof vorltablo palaces, as stations In the\nlarger cities. If tho public refuse to pro\nvide tho money for such projects, then\nthcro will bo a lull in Improvements of\nthis kind until conditions again change\nfor tho better and conditions In a young\nand progresslvo country are far moro\nlikely to recover than to retrograde.\nLow freight rates will encourage traf\nfic, -whereas high rates would discourage\nIt, a fact that was very clearly under\nstood and acted upon when debating was\nIn vogue.\nThe railroads were actuated to some\nextent in tholr movo to secure Increased\nrates by agitation for decreases; this\nagitation has been quashed.\nNew Rules on Street.\nSo the outlook may not bo do black\nafter all.\nThe public having consistently refused\nduring tho last three years to play with\nWall street under the old rules 10-polnt\nmarglng, easily wiped out now and safer\nrules have been drawn up, with every\npromise of success. Instead of being, a\nrank speculator, as ho was under tho\nmarginal method, the buyer can now\nclaim to bo an Investor. Onco he pays\nhis Urst Installment of $20 per share,\nho and not tho broker commands the\ndestiny of the stock; that 13 to say, the\nbuyer alone can glvo an order to sell It.\nOf course, tho monthly payments have\nto bo met regularly as In tho case of\nother purchases by Installment, but the\nbuyer knows tho extent of his liability,\nwhereas under tho old-fashioned margin\nho never knew whoro ho might stand.\nTho investor under tho news system\nshould bo oxtrcmely careful in selecting\na broker and should also havo a hard\nand fast agreement as to what would\nhappen wero the market to collapse Just\nafter tho first twenty points wore paid.\nShort Notes the Rule.\nSince January 1. 1D07, tho total out\nput of now securities by railroad and\nindustrial corporations In tho United\nStates has reached 56,379,01-1,880. Of this\ntotal, $1,093,716,802 has consisted of\nshort term notes. This I3 equivalent to\n17J per cent.\nThe railroads were responsible for\nSS8S.S00.002 of the notes, the balance of\nJ204.01G.S00 having been contributed by\nIndustrial and miscellaneous companies.\nThe largest percentage of notes was\nreached in 1007, namely almost ono\nfourth of tho total capital floated. In\ntho following year the proportion Just\nexceeded 21 per cent. Then there was\na drop In 1D09 to little moro than 5 per\ncent, tlnsre having been plentv of cheap\nmoney and unbounded conndenco in a\nreturn of prosperity throughout tho coun\ntry. Short term financing was again re\nsorted to last year on a fairly largo\nscale, tho ratio being 18 per cent. Dur\ning the current year, that is to say from\nJanuary 1 to Fobruary 21. tho note is\nsues havo been equivalent to 24 percent\nof the total capital distributed.\nl ThJre have been about six and a quar\nter million bales of cotton exported thin\nyear., about a million and three auarters\nmore than at the same time last year.\nThis cotton is not piled up at the ports\non the other side. While it Is true that\nthe stock of American cotton in Liver\npool Is J86.000 bales larger than It was\nat this tlmo a year aco, tho foreieners\nare still buylnir. and at the end of the\nseason the difference between the ex\nports of thl3 year and last will probably\nbo greater than it is today. The forelim\ners havo not bought cotton to hold out\nat IB cents a pound. They have boucht\nheavily only because they needed the\ncotton.\nNever in the history of the world has\nthere been as manv spindles in ODera\ntlon in England as thero havo been dur\ning the last bIx months. The many now\nmills are all running and so aro the old\nones. They will need more American\ncotton before they can cot now crop un\nless thero Is some radical chanso in\nconditions.\nIt begins to look as If there was not\ngplng to be as much cotton left for do\nmestic mills as there was last year, for\nIn spite of the free movement, the south\n13 no loiiKer full of cotton, as the char\nacter of tho cotton now movlne plainly\nshows, Tho outlook for tho rest of this\nyear is fully as good as It was at this\ntlmo a year ago. It looks as If American\nmills still have a great deal of cotton to\nbuy.\n\"HANDS OFF\" POLICY OF\nAUSTRIA IN BALKANS\nSpecial Cable to The Tribune.\nVIENNA, March 11. Whether there is\nreally danger of an immediate break be\ntween Austria and Germany or between\nTurkey and Austria or not, the question\nio agitating political leaders in Austria.\nWhile tho agitation is laid to certain\nnowspaporn It cannot bo denied that Aus\ntria will not be found wholly unprepared\nKhould a disturbance arise.\nAustria's foreign policy was to a cer\ntain extent net forth in a speech by Prince\nEsterhozy. at Buda Pest, before the house\nof delegates.\nWith reference to the criticisms leveled\nat tho minister's conservative policy, tho\nspeaker pointed to the formulating- of the\nBalkan policy by tho minister of foreign\naffairs, who desired to maintain tho status\nquo in tho Balkans In every respect,\nsought no adventures, and threatened no\none's safety. Tho demands of the mili\ntary administration wero not tho result of\nforeign policy. They were aimed solely at\ntho defense of tho monarchy. It was ob\nvious that the foreign minister could not\npursue a sound policy if ho knew that\nho had no force behind him.\nW th& dli6s fl\nI- yoni benefit hy its pleasing! aid\nto digestion?95 M\n66Won9t yon be g!ad of white teeth and t H\n1 purified breath merely by chewing the H\nw. gfiim with the flavor that's so hard to II\nchew out?95\nLook for the spear Your dealer should Ball It. The flavor lasts iJi\nBRITAIN NOT- YET UP TO\nWESTERN DIVORCE RECORD\nSpecial Cable to Tho Tribune.\nLONDON, March 11. Sir 'John Mac\ndonnell's latest report on the law courts\nIssued contains a long analysis of the\ndivorce coses. Tho conclusion is:\nDivorce petitions In 1J09 numbered 7S7.\nagainst 846 In 100S, but the decrees\ngranted numbered 685, against 672.\nIn almost ono-half of tho divorces tho\nmarrlago has lasted from ton to twenty\nyears, and In about one-third between\nfive and ton years. Petitioners for the\nmost part belong to tho middle classes.\nA small number are engaged in farming,\nmining or domestic service.\nOut of 110 potltions, eighty-one were\nby wives. But among merchant skip\npers, mates and teamen, postal em\nployees, civil servants, soldlors, and\nnaval seamen and police, the majority\nof tho petitions wero presented by hus\nbands. Out of tho thirty-five petitions\nInvolving actors, musicians and tho like,\ntwenty-two wore by wives.\nIn 40 per cent of tho unhappy mar\nriages there was no child and In 25 per\ncent there was only ono child of the\nunion. Parents of six 01 more children\nwere Involved in only one of every fifty\nPalmo Tablets\ntransform weak, broken-down, nervous\nWTOckB into magnificent types of physi\ncal perfection. They restore tho nervca\nand kidneys to their normal conditions\nand make you look and feel years\nyounger. Guaranteed. 50 cents. Book\nFroo. Tho S. R. Foil Co.. Cleveland. O.\nSOHEAMM-JOHNSON, DRUGS, FIVE\nSTORES.\nThe Car oj the Hour\n1911 Model\n30 Horsepower\nMotor\n4-Cyllnder, 4-Cycle,\nBore 4 Inches\nStroke 4J2 Inches\n108 Wheel Base.\nRoadster\nComplete With\nMAGNETO\n5 Lamps, Tuhe Horn\nand Generator.\nt\n$1000\n1 Year Guarantee.\nStudebaker Auto Co,\n2nd E. and 2nd So. I\n1 1\ndivorce casoB.\nTho numbers of petitions from tho\nworking classes wa3 270 out of tho total\nof 7S7. being slightly more than In 1908,\nand slightly fewer than In 1907.\nProbate of the will of Sir William Ag\nnew, tho famous art dealer and connois\nseur, has been granted in Manchester.\nTho gross value of tho porsonal and real\nestate as sworn was ?13,000.000. The\nonly charitable bcouest is a sum of $5000\nto the Genoral Hospital and Dispensary\nfor Sick Children at Pondlebury.\nTho -will of Lord WInlerstoko of Blag\ndon has been lodged for probato by the\nexecutors, tho estate being provisionally\nsworn at $5, 000. 000.\nPlague Sproads to Europe.\nSpecial Cable to Tho Tribune.\nBUCHAREST, March 11.. According to\na telegraphic communication reh\nfrom tho Roumanian society of Coasts\nllnople, tho Manch'urlan plague has.'i\nready spread to European Russia. Fa\nfatal cases havo been reported la ,1\ngovernment of Astrachan. It Is feai\nthat the epldomlc will be conveyed ft\nRoumanla, and the Roumanian govei\nment has decided to proclaim b. 1a\nrigorous quarantine\nI life. You aro like an online without jlfibj 'fl\nsteam you haren 't tho motive r)owor to keep tho machinery of your hody otafegipyif l\n5 working properly. Anything that will rostore your \"steam\" will make a new W&$$rWffl Aiil\nman of you. Drus have been tried and have failed. You know that; but KS5?5mS\nElectra-Vita will not fail; it is electricity, and \"electricity is life That is F&MSwBf A\n1 hpins r0qmre' and the PrPer 1168 of Electra-Vita will give you health aud- fl\nI Electra-Vita is a scientific device for saturating the human body with a wa B7!\npowerful but soothing current of electric life, for hours at a tiino, without tho EraSeS\nA least shock or unpleasant sensation. It generates a constant, unbroken stream o MssSwsf MU,I\nolectncity, which it sends coursinp through every nerve and tissue of the body RbWB\n1 restoring vitality and strenRth and giving evory weak or iuactive organ the fNUSInfl\npower to doits work as naturo intended. When 3'our body has sufficient elcctrio rJIlm3S iM\nenergy to satisfy the demands of nature, weakness and disease cannot exist. WSm' fl\n1 Ea-Vita is a self-charged bodv battery for home uao! It is not like SsSSKU\ni used :faradlc Dattries and other contrivances you may have seen or FH '-fl\ni .ren afe ,n'\"? n ?7 7,eak and unambitious will find that elec- B5I 'vfl\ntncitv, as supplied by Llectra-Vita, will quickly put them in good condition JfiSfTii\nr2G\"iaIl de.8, not live who cannot be made'a better man bv the annlica- wMSrWJMM 'fl\nratorof tChorage UBCd 11 tbat U th r\"aado3t mVigo- fBTTwwmt\nBecause you have experimented with faradic batteries or taken electric treni- ES&wJw fl\nment from physicians without being cured la no r